Foreign-invested Enterprises in Ho Chi Minh City Continue to Grow 
Foreign-invested enterprises in Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh City continued to
grow in the first half of this year.
The industrial production value of the foreign-invested enterprises
gained 8.133 trillion VND (560 million U.S. dollars) in the first six
months of this year, a 13.4 percent year-on-year increase, according to
a report of Vietnam News Agency on Wednesday.
The foreign-invested enterprises earned 618.5 million U.S. dollars from
exports in the reviewed period, 18.8 percent more than the same period
last year.
In regard to commerce and services, the foreign-invested enterprises'
turnover reached 798 billion VND (53.2 million U.S. dollars) with 546
billion VND (36.4 million U.S. dollars) coming from retail sales, up by
25 percent and 31 percent respectively as compared to the first half of
2000.
Consequently, foreign-invested enterprises in the city remitted 1.031
trillion VND (71 million U.S. dollars) to the country's state budget, a
year-on-year increase of 10.4 percent or 54 percent of the yearly plan.
